              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">SWCCG in Chandrila. The Metagame.</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=3534"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=3534"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=10058">David "Lirkas 'DDM'" Destefanis</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 10058 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This article won&#8217;t change your way to play the game, so feel free to rate low.
It&#8217;s only there to make you smile, and to know a little more of how SWCCG is played around the World. :-)</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Hello everyone,<br>
<br>
It&#146;s been a while since I wanted to write an article about my beloved SWCCG Region, so here are some facts:<br>
<br>
A) Chandrila ?!?<br>
<br>
Chandrila is a little SWCCG Region. Geograficaly put, it&#146;s Italy ! :-)<br>
<br>
B) Number of Players.<br>
<br>
Chandrila doesn&#146;t have many players... never had, and will never have. I think that we have some 30 active players in the whole country, at most. Since Italy has a geografical shape akin to a &quot;foot&quot;, players are usually far from each other, and need to travel a lot (at least for European standards ! ^_^) to get to important tournaments.<br>
<br>
C) Tournaments.<br>
<br>
For the small number of players, Chandrila is more active than it should. Sometimes (usually 3 times a year) a big tournament is organized in Rome (geograficaly center of ITaly) with some 18 people showing off, with players usually coming from a long way.<br>
<br>
D) Skill Level.<br>
<br>
Chandrila has the same problems as many small regions out there. Few people means few playtest, and slow improvement.<br>
There are some skilled players, but the plain truth is just that: Chandrila players lack experience to perform well in international events. They may build great decks, but theory isn&#146;t enough. You have to practice to play better and win.<br>
Usually Chandrila players try to fill the gap by trying the new cards, looking at Decktech (a few) and sometimes by traveling outside (fewer still).<br>
All in all, there are some good players in Chandrila, and I did always think that only by placing well at international events (or at least not placing bad !^_^) this can be attested.<br>
This is the case (it wasn&#146;t in the past ! ^_^) so I feel a little more proud of Chandrila now. ;-)<br>
<br>
E) Playstyle and Metagame.<br>
<br>
Chandrila playstyle is waaaaay conservative. No, I&#146;m not speaking of S/A wars here. Chandrilla playstyle is always more &quot;defensive&quot; than everyone else out there.<br>
Basically they understand the power of offense, but don&#146;t play it that good. So not to get crushed by some other decks out there, they stick to, base, solid decks.<br>
The real pain in Chandrilla is that eventually almost all players can improve a &quot;somewhat&quot; base deck into something solid, or at least annoying for whatever top international deck.<br>
The truth is that in Chandrila, you cannot metagame to think you&#146;re gonna face particular deck types only. No.<br>
You always know you&#146;re going to face weird decks, or some that will loose against Deck A and B, but crush Deck C (which is, incidentally, the one you&#146;re using), and because you cannot have even a slight idea of what kind of deck you&#146;ll be facing, there&#146;s a chance to face a rogue deck even at the top tables, since the rogue player could have luckily faced all favorable match-ups.<br>
Metagaming in Chandrila is then totally &quot;out of bonds&quot;.<br>
You name a top deck international, like Senate Ties, well, you know that in Chandrila there will be AT LEAST 2 players playing decks that totally kills it, and what the worst is that often they didn&#146;t build their decks vs. Senate Ties to start with !<br>
So for players like me, who play in AND out Chandrila often, this usually means you have to play decks 6-7 cards different when you go vs. Chandrila players. And some you best not to play them at all ! ;-)<br>
<br>
F) the EVIL Chandrila players.<br>
<br>
Chandrila has a knack for one attitude.<br>
They like to take you off guard.<br>
I&#146;ve seen players go to a big tournament with &quot;one-way effective&quot; decks, like Troopers, and even if loosing all the time vs. HBXWings, they&#146;ll just don&#146;t care and have fun by totally crush the other ground deck out there.<br>
I&#146;ve seen Ewoks (only luckily resisting Spear attacks because I was drawing blind &quot;7&quot;s !).<br>
I&#146;ve seen Destiny 7 Baragwins. Everything.<br>
Even Operatives, yes, still now !<br>
The only thing we don&#146;t see is DBO ! (so we&#146;re not that crazy... ^_^)<br>
Chandrila players just love ripping your all carefully constructed deck and strategy out of the window.<br>
So everytime they&#146;ll start construct a deck, than in the middle put something weird, unexpected, or just plainly inefficient, and smile, proud of it !<br>
I&#146;m a Chandrila player also... with a twist: I like unexpected decks, but I hate players trying to copy and play the top international decktypes that I don&#146;t like ! (like COmbat) So everytime I see one I make a point of crushing it ! ^__^<br>
And truthfully I dread the Chandrila Regional... <br>
The Regional is a nightmare, for me, for deck builing. The REAL problem is to find a deck that will get me to the Finals.<br>
Europeans, and Worlds, in comparison, are easy. THERE the problem is sometimes lack of practice, not deckbuilding.<br>
<br>
Sum up:<br>
<br>
All in all,  Chandrila is a fun region where to play.<br>
And a hint: don&#146;t think a deck here, in DeckTech, will work for your Regional. <br>
The best decks here in DT would work at World events.<br>
Your own region might have a different meta, so be careful.<br>
Change at least some cards.<br>
Play the game, and have fun doing it ! <br>
that all it counts !<br>
<br>
Sorry for those I wasted their time.<br>
I just wanted you to look at another corner of the world.<br>
Cheers,<br>
<br>
DDM </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=3534"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=3534"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=3534" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
